00:00:30.210 --> 00:00:31.620
I'll also tell you how to get

17
00:00:31.620 --> 00:00:34.230
started and give a
quick demonstration.

18
00:00:34.230 --> 00:00:37.380
Historically, people
saved most data in

19
00:00:37.380 --> 00:00:40.220
structured formats that were
relatively easy to search.

20
00:00:40.220 --> 00:00:41.990
For example, information entered

21
00:00:41.990 --> 00:00:43.910
into databases via forms or

22
00:00:43.910 --> 00:00:45.950
saved and spreadsheets
is pretty easy

23
00:00:45.950 --> 00:00:48.595
to analyze even at
very high volumes.

24
00:00:48.595 --> 00:00:51.100
Increasingly, we capture data in

25
00:00:51.100 --> 00:00:52.700
less structured
formats that are more

26
00:00:52.700 --> 00:00:54.935
difficult to analyze
on a large scale.

27
00:00:54.935 --> 00:00:58.790
In particular, the speech in
audio and video files needs

28
00:00:58.790 --> 00:01:00.290
to be recorded as text

29
00:01:00.290 --> 00:01:03.220
before it can be
searched or categorized.

30
00:01:03.220 --> 00:01:06.360
Traditionally,
converting audio content

31
00:01:06.360 --> 00:01:09.065
to text has required a lot
of human intervention.

32
00:01:09.065 --> 00:01:11.930
Someone has to play back the
recording and capture all of

33
00:01:11.930 --> 00:01:14.000
the speaker's words
in text form and then

34
00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:16.235
review and edit the
transcribed content.

35
00:01:16.235 --> 00:01:19.130
Even with the benefit of
a speech-to-text tool,

36
00:01:19.130 --> 00:01:22.055
a lot of editing and
formatting is required.

37
00:01:22.055 --> 00:01:25.250
This is particularly true
for outputs that require

38
00:01:25.250 --> 00:01:26.870
high levels of accuracy and

39
00:01:26.870 --> 00:01:29.320
readability like video subtitles.

40
00:01:29.320 --> 00:01:31.640
The high level of
effort to manually

41
00:01:31.640 --> 00:01:33.980
convert these media to
text means that only

42
00:01:33.980 --> 00:01:36.350
the most critical items
are transcribed and

43
00:01:36.350 --> 00:01:39.355
valuable information
may be overlooked.

44
00:01:39.355 --> 00:01:41.570
Amazon Transcribe can help

45
00:01:41.570 --> 00:01:43.505
you address these
potential barriers.

46
00:01:43.505 --> 00:01:45.380
Amazon Transcribe is

47
00:01:45.380 --> 00:01:48.905
a fully managed and continually
trained ASR service

48
00:01:48.905 --> 00:01:52.175
that accepts common audio
formats including WAV,

49
00:01:52.175 --> 00:01:55.160
MP3, MP4, and FLAC,

50
00:01:55.160 --> 00:01:56.870
and can accurately transcribe

51
00:01:56.870 --> 00:01:59.845
both low fidelity and
high fidelity audio.

52
00:01:59.845 --> 00:02:01.880
This makes it a natural fit for

53
00:02:01.880 --> 00:02:04.145
use cases such as
transcribing customer

54
00:02:04.145 --> 00:02:07.070
service calls into
analyzable data or

55
00:02:07.070 --> 00:02:09.200
generating subtitles for videos

56
00:02:09.200 --> 00:02:11.425
with a high level of accuracy.

57
00:02:11.425 --> 00:02:14.420
Amazon Transcribe
uses deep learning to

58
00:02:14.420 --> 00:02:17.195
provide accurate and
quick transcriptions.

59
00:02:17.195 --> 00:02:19.910
It was designed to make
it easy for you to get

60
00:02:19.910 --> 00:02:21.500
even greater accuracy and

61
00:02:21.500 --> 00:02:24.155
usefulness from the
transcribed output.

62
00:02:24.155 --> 00:02:26.990
For example, the output is

63
00:02:26.990 --> 00:02:30.170
not just one long
uninterrupted string of text.

64
00:02:30.170 --> 00:02:33.710
Instead, Amazon
Transcribe uses machine

65
00:02:33.710 --> 00:02:34.910
learning to add in

66
00:02:34.910 --> 00:02:37.520
punctuation and
grammatical formatting.

67
00:02:37.520 --> 00:02:41.170
So the texts you get back
is immediately usable.

68
00:02:41.170 --> 00:02:45.100
Amazon Transcribe also
timestamps every word,

69
00:02:45.100 --> 00:02:46.730
which makes it easy to align

70
00:02:46.730 --> 00:02:48.650
subtitles for close captioning.

71
00:02:48.650 --> 00:02:50.750
It also makes it easy to index.

72
00:02:50.750 --> 00:02:53.075
Transcripts include
confidence levels

73
00:02:53.075 --> 00:02:55.280
for each word of the
transcribed output,

74
00:02:55.280 --> 00:02:57.140
making it easy to determine where

75
00:02:57.140 --> 00:03:00.710
more editing or quality
assurance may be required.

76
00:03:00.710 --> 00:03:03.500
Amazon Transcribe also
helps you mitigate

77
00:03:03.500 --> 00:03:06.185
issues with source audio
to improve accuracy.

78
00:03:06.185 --> 00:03:07.910
For example, you can upload

79
00:03:07.910 --> 00:03:10.370
custom vocabulary
that can help improve

80
00:03:10.370 --> 00:03:13.100
the accuracy if the content
you're transcribing has

81
00:03:13.100 --> 00:03:16.520
industry-specific terms like
medical or legal terms.

82
00:03:16.520 --> 00:03:18.785
You can choose the language
of the source file.

83
00:03:18.785 --> 00:03:20.695
The supported
languages are listed,

84
00:03:20.695 --> 00:03:23.990
and Amazon Transcribe
attribute speech to

85
00:03:23.990 --> 00:03:25.580
different speakers to make it

86
00:03:25.580 --> 00:03:27.935
easier to interpret the output.

87
00:03:27.935 --> 00:03:30.290
Because Amazon Transcribe was

88
00:03:30.290 --> 00:03:32.590
designed to be easy
for developers to use,

89
00:03:32.590 --> 00:03:35.240
there are only a few
steps to get started.

90
00:03:35.240 --> 00:03:37.820
You don't need to understand
how the underlying models

91
00:03:37.820 --> 00:03:39.170
work and you don't need to

92
00:03:39.170 --> 00:03:41.135
build your own machine
learning models.

93
00:03:41.135 --> 00:03:42.785
You invoke the service via

94
00:03:42.785 --> 00:03:45.260
API and with a few lines of code,

95
00:03:45.260 --> 00:03:48.740
you're ready to transcribe
files on Amazon S3.

96
00:03:48.740 --> 00:03:52.490
You can easily initiate the
transcription operation via

97
00:03:52.490 --> 00:03:54.740
the AWS management console

98
00:03:54.740 --> 00:03:57.745
and you can test the service
via the console too.

99
00:03:57.745 --> 00:04:01.295
Amazon Transcribe offers
secure communication

100
00:04:01.295 --> 00:04:02.510
between the service and

101
00:04:02.510 --> 00:04:05.435
your applications
through SSL encryption.

102
00:04:05.435 --> 00:04:09.365
You can access your
transcriptions via assigned URLs.

103
00:04:09.365 --> 00:04:11.735
You can also make sure
that information is

104
00:04:11.735 --> 00:04:13.850
kept secure and confidential by

105
00:04:13.850 --> 00:04:16.414
controlling access
to Amazon Transcribe

106
00:04:16.414 --> 00:04:19.400
through AWS IAM policies.

107
00:04:19.400 --> 00:04:21.830
The service integrates
easily with

108
00:04:21.830 --> 00:04:25.705
other AWS services such
as Amazon Comprehend,

109
00:04:25.705 --> 00:04:30.905
Amazon ES, Amazon Translate,
and Amazon Athena.

110
00:04:30.905 --> 00:04:32.885
You can easily leverage

111
00:04:32.885 --> 00:04:35.270
powerful deep learning
models combined with

112
00:04:35.270 --> 00:04:38.540
highly scalable index
searching and analysis tools

113
00:04:38.540 --> 00:04:42.500
to reap high-value from your
audio and video content.

114
00:04:42.500 --> 00:04:44.860
Here are a few examples.

115
00:04:44.860 --> 00:04:48.920
A call center uses Amazon
Transcribe to produce

116
00:04:48.920 --> 00:04:51.410
transcriptions of
low-fidelity phone calls

117
00:04:51.410 --> 00:04:53.150
with high accuracy.

118
00:04:53.150 --> 00:04:55.640
The center uses Amazon Comprehend

119
00:04:55.640 --> 00:04:57.350
on the transcribed data to

120
00:04:57.350 --> 00:04:58.940
identify key phrases and

121
00:04:58.940 --> 00:05:02.195
customer sentiments so that
they can classify the calls.

122
00:05:02.195 --> 00:05:05.285
They use Amazon Athena
to query the data and

123
00:05:05.285 --> 00:05:07.490
Amazon QuickSight to visualize

124
00:05:07.490 --> 00:05:10.255
the results and analyze trends.

125
00:05:10.255 --> 00:05:13.620
The Human Resources
Department uses

126
00:05:13.620 --> 00:05:15.650
Amazon Transcribe to generate

127
00:05:15.650 --> 00:05:18.260
transcriptions of meetings
and training sessions,

128
00:05:18.260 --> 00:05:21.395
then indexes the results
using Amazon ES.

129
00:05:21.395 --> 00:05:23.780
Internal stakeholders
can quickly search for

130
00:05:23.780 --> 00:05:27.335
content on demand to
locate topics of interest.

131
00:05:27.335 --> 00:05:30.170
A video production business uses

132
00:05:30.170 --> 00:05:32.060
Amazon Transcribe to produce

133
00:05:32.060 --> 00:05:35.120
transcriptions of audio
tracks for subtitles.

134
00:05:35.120 --> 00:05:38.480
Limited editing is done
on the output files and

135
00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:40.340
the quality assurance
team can focus

136
00:05:40.340 --> 00:05:42.905
on sections that have
lower confidence ratings.

137
00:05:42.905 --> 00:05:45.730
Using the timestamps in
the transcript file,

138
00:05:45.730 --> 00:05:49.325
they can easily align the
captions with the video.

139
00:05:49.325 --> 00:05:51.560
They use Amazon
Translate to convert

140
00:05:51.560 --> 00:05:54.365
the transcript into
additional languages.

141
00:05:54.365 --> 00:05:57.245
You can even translate
conversations.

