read the translated
message to the recipient.

150
00:06:17.195 --> 00:06:19.065
To get started, you'll need to

151
00:06:19.065 --> 00:06:21.050
save the file you
want to transcribe on

152
00:06:21.050 --> 00:06:25.100
Amazon S3 stored in a bucket
with the proper permissions.

153
00:06:25.100 --> 00:06:29.300
The files must be in one of
four formats; FLAC, MP3,

154
00:06:29.300 --> 00:06:33.650
MP4, or WAV, and they must
be less than two hours long.

155
00:06:33.650 --> 00:06:35.810
For best results, source files

156
00:06:35.810 --> 00:06:37.640
should use lossless compression,

157
00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:39.755
FLAC or WAV, and recording

158
00:06:39.755 --> 00:06:42.110
should be done in a
low-noise environment.

159
00:06:42.110 --> 00:06:44.360
You'll want to limit
crosstalk too.

160
00:06:44.360 --> 00:06:46.730
You'll need an AWS account with

161
00:06:46.730 --> 00:06:48.335
an IAM user who has

162
00:06:48.335 --> 00:06:51.410
full access to the
transcribed API calls,

163
00:06:51.410 --> 00:06:54.245
and you should be
familiar with the CLI.

164
00:06:54.245 --> 00:06:56.840
You'll also need a text editor.

165
00:06:56.840 --> 00:06:59.360
We also recommend that you

166
00:06:59.360 --> 00:07:01.160
review the developer's
guide which you can

167
00:07:01.160 --> 00:07:05.500
find in the AWS documentation
under Amazon Transcribe.

